                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00115 European War 1939/507: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Palmer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-12T11:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 12, 1940—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 12—10:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>75. Reference my telegram No. 72, August 8. Leading local British residents,
                    including Canadians, have escaped to Palestine mostly by night, some
                    disguised.</p>
                <p>French authorities here are apparently not displeased at this evasion of an order
                    that they privately regard as inspired by Berlin and that constitutes another
                    obstacle to British approval of the clearing agreement with Palestine which had
                    already been made contingent upon release of British seamen still interned here
                    contrary to advice of High Commissioner Puaux.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Palmer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
